{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12928"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12928"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.06,0.03,0.13,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44395"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29293"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2522"},{"type":"tags","id":"2957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12907"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44395"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man who was recently diagnosed with monoclonal gammopathy of uncertain significance (MGUS) now presents with sudden onset, bilateral swelling of his legs. In addition, he also noticed bruising around his eyes and an inability to raise his hands over his head. His medical history is significant for obesity for which he manages through lifestyle modifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has prominent, rounded protrusions over the anterior aspect of his deltoid muscles. His tongue also appears large. He has bilateral pitting oedema to the level of his knee. His blood pressure is 137/74 mmHg, pulse 84/min temperature 37.3C, respiratory rate 14/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 98% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA dipstick urinalysis returned +++ proteinuria. A 24-hour urine protein is returned as 5.2g/24 hours. Serum HbA1c is returned as 4.5% and albumin is 24g/L (normal: 32-45 g/L).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his renal impairment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amyloid light chain nephropathy","Minimal change disease","Diabetic nephropathy","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis","IgA nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe triad of macroglossia, shoulder pad sign and raccoon eye, in combination with the presence of nephrotic syndrome (proteinuria \u0026gt;3.5g/24 hours and background of plasma cell dyscrasia, should raise suspicion for \u003Cstrong\u003Elight chain amyloidosis (AL)\u003C/strong\u003E. AL is a systemic disease that causes amyloid light chain protein deposition within different organs, including the kidney and heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimal change disease\u003C/strong\u003E is another cause of nephrotic syndrome. It is less likely to be the patient\u0027s diagnosis given his significant history and symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause nephrotic syndrome, but is only seen in patients with progressive diabetes. His serum HbA1c is 4.5%, which indicates good glycaemic control over the past 3 months. He was not diagnosed with diabetes mellitus, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a systemic ANCA positive vasculitis that predominately affects the respiratory tract and kidneys. It usually does not manifest with nephrotic syndrome on first appearance; rather patients would have microscopic haematuria and a gradual decline in renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E rarely causes nephrotic syndrome. Rather, it usually presents with microscopic or macroscopic haematuria a few days after a non-specific upper respiratory tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In patients presenting with nephrotic syndrome on a background of plasma cell dyscrasia, amyloidosis should be suspected"],"references":["Gurung R, Li T. Renal Amyloidosis: Presentation, Diagnosis, and Management. Am J Med. 2022 Apr;135 Suppl 1:S38-S43. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2022.01.003. Epub 2022 Jan 24. PMID: 35085515.","Rawla P, Limaiem F, Hashmi MF. IgA Nephropathy (Berger Disease) [Updated 2023 Jul 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538214/","Garlapati P, Qurie A. Granulomatosis With Polyangiitis. [Updated 2022 Dec 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557827/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29293"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12928"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29293"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-18T08:21:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-18T08:21:00+09:30"},"relationsh